The poets also use other aspects of form to present the reality of conict.
Owen uses a regular ABBAC rhyme scheme to emphasise the monotony experienced
by the soldiers. Despite this regularity, halfrhymes such as “wire” and “war”
create a sense of jarring discomfort that mirrors the soldiers’ suffering.
On the other hand, in ‘Belfast Confetti’, Carson uses enjambment and uneven line
lengths to add to the poem’s broken and irregular rhythm, echoing the confusion
experienced by the speaker. The irregular rhythm is heightened by caesurae,
such as in “Crimea / Street. Dead end again.” These help to create a sense of
fragmentation and show that the speaker is struggling to think clearly.
